author: @Anton-wz4yg
text: You should not use max pooling or any pooling layers in your network. The translational invariance that they offer is something you actually want to avoid: your network wants to know where EXACTLY the buildings, agents etc. are. Check the DQN architecture for example. I know that you are not using reinforcement learning techniques to train, but the same theory applies on the deep networks as in RL. Also dropout has not shown to be useful in reinforcement learning. You kind of want to overfit on the environment that you train on, so from the theory dropout does not make sense. I have not tested myself whether they impede performance, so I might be wrong here. So to make it as simple as possible I would just remove dropout and max pooling layers.
